{"title":"Walk Wisely on Graph: Knowledge Graph Reasoning with Dual Agents via Efficient Guidance-Exploration","domain":"RL","seeds":[{"problem":"Multi-hop knowledge graph reasoning with RL suffers from sparse rewards and exponentially large action spaces. Prior dual-agent methods (e.g., CURL) can misguide the low-level agent by forcing it to mimic a high-level policy, causing policy shift and low training efficiency, especially for long-distance reasoning on sparse KGs.","method":"FULORA introduces a dual-agent hierarchical RL framework where a high-level agent (GIANT) walks on a cluster-level KG and a low-level agent (DWARF) walks on the original entity-level KG, sharing history via an information-sharing vector. It proposes an efficient guidance-exploration mechanism: a constraint reward based on cosine state similarity between GIANT and DWARF that is only applied when GIANT reaches the correct cluster. The trade-off is optimized with REINFORCE and a state-dependent Lagrange multiplier λ(s_e)∈[0,1], learned via a cross-entropy objective to increase guidance when similarity is low and encourage exploration when similarity is high. This reduces harmful coupling, stabilizes learning, and improves long-distance reasoning performance."},{"problem":"The high-level agent on the cluster graph receives extremely sparse binary rewards, leading to near-random early policies and poor guidance quality for the low-level agent.","method":"FULORA introduces Dynamic Path Feedback, a reward-shaping objective for GIANT that scores entire rollouts using a similarity-based potential toward the target cluster rather than rewarding only terminal success. The shaped reward R_D augments the default reward with a similarity term scaled by α, and the authors prove that the optimal policy under shaping is consistent with the default-reward MDP. This accelerates convergence, yields more reliable guidance (higher cluster state similarity), and boosts accuracy on long-path queries."},{"problem":"On the entity-level KG, many neighbors and relations per node make it hard for the low-level agent to focus on query-relevant edges, particularly in dense KGs and long-path settings.","method":"DWARF integrates a graph attention mechanism into its LSTM-based policy to compute an attention vector over neighbors conditioned on the query and history (following AttnPath’s formulation), and feeds this into the policy network alongside entity/relation embeddings. This focuses exploration on the most relevant relations and neighbors, improving local decision quality and complementing high-level guidance; ablations show notable gains, especially on dense KGs (e.g., FB15K-237)."}]}
